    "# Module 5: Input and Output\n",
    "\n",
    "## 1. Output Using `print()`\n",
    "The `print()` function displays text or calculations on the screen. Let's look at different ways to print.\n",
    "\n",
    "### A. Basic Print\n",
    "Prints simple values or variables.\n",
    "```python\n",
    "print(\"Hello World\")\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### B. Printing Multiple Values\n",
    "You can print multiple variables separated by commas. Python automatically adds a space between them.\n",
    "```python\n",
    "name = \"Rahul\"\n",
    "age = 25\n",
    "print(name, age)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### C. The `sep` Parameter (Separator)\n",
    "By default, multiple values are separated by spaces. You can change this using `sep`.\n",
    "```python\n",
    "print(\"Python\", \"Data\", \"Science\", sep=\"-\")\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### D. The `end` Parameter\n",
    "By default, `print()` ends with a new line. You can change what it prints at the end (like a space or comma) using `end`.\n",
    "```python\n",
    "print(\"Hello\", end=\" \")\n",
    "print(\"World\")\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### E. Escape Characters\n",
    "* `\\n`: Moves to a **New Line**.\n",
    "* `\\t`: Adds a **Tab Space**.\n",
    "```python\n",
    "print(\"Hello\\nWorld\")\n",
    "print(\"Name\\tAge\")\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### F. String Concatenation\n",
    "Joining strings together using the `+` operator. (Note: both values must be strings!).\n",
    "```python\n",
    "name = \"Rahul\"\n",
    "print(\"My name is \" + name)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### G. f-Strings (Formatted Strings) 🌟\n",
    "**Highly Recommended!** f-strings are the easiest and cleanest way to print variables inside text. Simply put an `f` before the quotes, and place variables inside curly braces `{}`.\n",
    "```python\n",
    "name = \"Rahul\"\n",
    "age = 25\n",
    "print(f\"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.\")\n",
    "```\n"
   ]
